[2] South Korea - WHO update - 19 Jun 2015
Date: 19 Jun 2015
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response Disease Outbreak News 19 Jun 2015
http://who.int/csr/don/19-june-2015-mers-korea/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Republic of Korea - 19 Jun 2015
------------------------------------------
Situation in Korea
Between [17 and 19 Jun 2015], the National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea notified WHO of 12 additional confirmed cases of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV) alongside 5 additional deaths.

Additional information on the outbreak in Korea
To date, a total of 166 MERS-CoV cases, including 24 deaths, have been reported. One of the 166 cases is the case that was confirmed in China and also notified by the National IHR Focal Point of China.

The median age of the patients is 68.5 years old (ranging from 16 to 87 years old). The majority of cases are men (60 percent). Twenty-one cases (7.9 percent) are health care professionals. To date, all cases (excluding the index case) have been linked to a single chain of transmission and are associated with health care facilities.

Detailed information concerning MERS-CoV cases in the Republic of Korea can be found in a separate document ([see http://who.int/emergencies/mers-cov/MERS-CoV-cases-rok.pdf for a line listing of cases, http://who.int/csr/disease/coronavirus_infections/maps-charts/en/ for maps and epicurves related to the outbreak]).

Public health response
The government of the Republic of Korea continues to implement intense case and contact management activities. As of [19 Jun 2015], 5930 contacts are being monitored while a total of 5535 contacts have been released. The number of new cases occurring each day appears to be declining. This suggests that the containment measures in place are contributing to reduce the rate of new infections.

On [16 Jun 2015], the Director-General of the World Health Organization convened the 9th Meeting of the Emergency Committee on MERS-CoV under the International Health Regulations. The WHO Secretariat provided the Committee with updates on the epidemiology of MERS-CoV in the Republic of Korea and China. The Committee expressed the need for all countries to be better prepared for the unanticipated possibility of an outbreak but concluded that MERS-CoV does not currently meet the conditions to be classified as a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.

Global situation
Globally, since September 2012, WHO has been notified of 1333 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 471 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The WHO update reconfirms the MOH report of yesterday (see MERS-CoV (71): Thailand ex Oman, South Korea, Saudi Arabia, UAE 20150618.3447481). For those who are interested in more epidemiologic details on the situation in South Korea, I strongly recommend going to the links on the WHO website where there is a line listing of all 166 cases with details on each of the cases as well as maps and epicurves on the outbreak. Thanks to the South Korean MOH and WHO for making all of this data available.
http://who.int/emergencies/mers-cov/MERS-CoV-cases-rok.pdf for a line listing of cases, http://who.int/csr/disease/coronavirus_infections/maps-charts/en/ for maps and epicurves related to the outbreak]).

On the global level, there have now been 1333 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection including at least 471 deaths that have been reported to WHO. - Mod.MPP]

