Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is interesting to see that the WHO SEARO office had sent out an alert to the member countries before the case in Thailand was identified. Clearly the outbreak in South Korea was a wake-up call globally about the high mobility of people -- the fact that we do live in a global village with constant travel and exchange between people from all countries. - Mod.MPP]

******
[6] Media tidbits
Date: 19 Jun 2015

Japan
http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/06/19/national/science-health/five-suspected-mers-victims-japan-arrived-south-korea/#.VYQ9DvlVikp
"Five people in Japan who were suspected of being infected with Middle East respiratory syndrome had broken home quarantine in South Korea, health minister Yasuhisa Shiozaki said Thursday [18 Jun 2015]. In South Korea, anyone put under home quarantine after coming into contact with a MERS-infected person or staying in the victim's home or hospital is barred from leaving the country. Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga said South Korean officials notified Japan that 2 Japanese and 3 South Korean citizens traveled to Japan while under quarantine. The Japanese government monitored the 5 but none showed symptoms of MERS, Suga said. Four have passed the MERS incubation period of 14 days, but the 5th person, as well as another Japanese found to have had contact with one of the 5 while in South Korea, are still being monitored, he added." [Human behavior....but in fairness it was unclear if these individuals were told about quarantine before they left. -Mod.MPP]

Viet Nam
http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/928027.shtml
"Vietnam's Ministry of Health on Friday [19 Jun 2015] denied a rumor of one patient infected with the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) in Hanoi. According to a press release, a rumor spreading in a social network stated that the MERS patient, a South Korean who entered Vietnam on [10 Jun 2015], is being isolated for medical treatment in capital Hanoi by the ministry." [If any of our subscribers have more information on this we'd greatly appreciate receiving it. At times social media can alert earlier events, at times it can serve as rumor mongers... - Mod.MPP]

Singapore
http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/928020.shtml
"The Middle Eastern Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) will arrive in Singapore sooner or later due to the country's global connectivity, said Singapore's Health Minister Gan Kim Yong on Friday [19 Jun 2015]. Gan's comment echoes with Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong's remarks on [11 Jun 2015]. Lee thought that it is a "matter of time" before Singapore has its first MERS case due to its inter- connectivity, therefore the city state must get prepared for MERS." [pragmatic and realistic - Mod.MPP]

Cambodia
https://www.cambodiadaily.com/news/as-mers-spreads-govt-says-its-prepared-86039/
"Following the 1st case of the potentially deadly Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) being confirmed in Thailand on Thursday [18 Jun 2015], government officials in Cambodia said entry points into the country were already equipped to prevent the disease from spreading here." [Airport screening is in place. - Mod.MPP]
